Inscription on a fountain, recorded by G. D'Annunzio: "Spectarunt nuptas hie se Mors atque Voluptas—Unus (fama ferat), quern quo, vultus erat: Death and pleasure already saw themselves wedded, and their two faces made only one face)."

Apparently there is a folk story about someone drowning the woman he loved inside that exact fountain. A term used for young women was "sealed fountain" (with similar meaning as "secret garden"): thus water to water; dust to dust.

Maximilian I and his wife Mary had to talk to each other in Latin at first, wonderful language to fall in love through. They would read chivalric romances together and she cheered for him at tournaments against the other knights. When he realized she was dying he was inconsolable

They actually had to bring Johannes Trithemius the necromancer to him to channel her image from death. You can trace a luminous genealogy of thinkers (von Cusa, Leibniz, Guenon) of clarity and order and a darkcel genealogy (him, Paracelsus, Evola) of good-hearted magus occultists

Basically at one point the army tried to convince people that having nuclear blast testing pollution is actually good for you and now supplement salesmen use the word to tell people to do river swims before breakfast or take whiskey shots. This is why we need #ConceptualHistory.

Just a heads-up, but when you read Dr. R. Peat talking about "hormesis" being bad, he's not talking about like meme cold showers or barefoot runs or whatever, back in his day it was a term used by the nuclear industry to shill for military atom bomb testing and unnecessary X-rays
